From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: pai-nix <pai-nix@localhost>
Date: Mon, 4 May 2026 17:15:00 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 21/21] Add systemd user unit for Pulse on Linux (launchd parity)

Upstream: applicable to all Linux installs of upstream PAI v5.0.0+ —
the gap is platform-shape, not Nix-specific. macOS path is unchanged.

Patch 0002 added Linux support to manage.sh by introducing start_direct
(nohup bun) and stop_direct (PID-file kill). That brings Pulse up on a
fresh `pai --force-install`, but only until the first crash or graceful
shutdown — there is no auto-start on user login, no restart on crash,
and no persistence across reboots. macOS gets all three via
com.pai.pulse.plist `RunAtLoad=true` + `KeepAlive=true` + launchd's
session lifecycle. Linux had nothing equivalent, so manage.sh
intentionally documented restart-via-manage.sh in the install wizard
copy (patch 0004). This patch closes the gap on every distro that ships
systemd-user — i.e., the overwhelming majority of desktop/server Linux
installs in 2026.

Reproduction (any systemd-user Linux):

  $ ./result/bin/pai --force-install
  ✓ PAI Pulse installed and verified on port 31337
  $ bash ~/.claude/PAI/PULSE/manage.sh stop
  PAI Pulse stopped
  # Log out, log back in. Pulse is gone — no auto-start.
  $ curl -sS http://localhost:31337/health
  curl: (7) Failed to connect to localhost port 31337
  # Same outcome after reboot. Same outcome if pulse.ts crashes
  # (no respawn — start_direct's `nohup &` is fire-and-forget).

Fix — install a systemd user unit equivalent to com.pai.pulse.plist:

  1. Detect systemd-user availability — `$XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/systemd`
     directory exists AND systemctl is in PATH. systemctl alone is
     insufficient: it ships in PATH inside chroots and minimal
     container images where the per-user manager is not running.
     Distros without systemd-user (Alpine, raw containers, NixOS
     without systemd-as-PID-1) fall through to the existing
     start_direct path. macOS skips this branch entirely via
     $IS_MACOS.

  2. write_unit() writes ~/.config/systemd/user/pai-pulse.service
     with:
       - ExecStart=$BUN_PATH run pulse.ts (absolute bun, same
         resolution chain manage.sh already established).
       - Restart=always, RestartSec=30 — mirrors launchd
         KeepAlive=true + ThrottleInterval=30.
       - ConditionPathExists=$PULSE_DIR/pulse.ts — fail-soft if
         Pulse isn't installed yet (rare race during first install,
         but cheap to guard).
       - Environment="PATH=$PATH" — bake the install-time PATH so
         claude/bun/jq/curl/git resolve regardless of how
         systemd-user inherits its session env. Whoever ran
         `manage.sh install` (the pai installer wrapper, the user's
         shell, or a packaging tool) already has a working PATH;
         capturing it gives the daemon the same toolchain its
         install context had. Bun's which("claude") otherwise
         falls back to ~/.local/bin/claude, which doesn't exist
         on most Linux installs and never on NixOS (claude lives
         under /nix/store via ~/.nix-profile/bin), so an explicit
         PATH is required for github-work and inference checks to
         function from the daemon. Re-running `manage.sh install`
         after a PATH change re-bakes the unit.
       - StandardOutput/StandardError=append:.../logs/pulse-*.log
         — preserves continuity with the launchd plist's
         file-based logging. Useful for `tail -f` debug without
         needing journalctl filters.
       - WantedBy=default.target — start on user login.

  3. Wire the systemd path into `start)`, `stop)`, `status)`,
     `install)`, and `uninstall)`. Each action gates on
     `$IS_SYSTEMD && [ -f "$SERVICE_DST" ]` before dispatching to
     systemctl, falling back to start_direct/stop_direct/PID-file
     logic if the unit isn't present yet (e.g. `manage.sh start`
     before `install`).

Co-existence:

  Patch 0002 added IS_MACOS detection, start_direct/stop_direct
  helpers, and gated `case start)` + `case stop)` on $IS_MACOS. This
  patch extends those gates with an `elif $IS_SYSTEMD` branch and
  adds write_unit alongside the direct helpers. Hunks live in
  adjacent line ranges but do not overlap with 0002's introduced
  lines. Patches 0004 and 0019 mention manage.sh in their headers
  but only modify PAI-Install/* files — no diff overlap.

  macOS path: every new branch is `elif $IS_SYSTEMD ...`. On macOS
  $IS_MACOS=true short-circuits the if-chain at the first branch,
  same as before this patch. The only structural change in the
  macOS branch is that stop_direct now lives inside the IS_MACOS
  block in `stop)` and `uninstall)` (previously called
  unconditionally after the if-fi). Net macOS behavior identical
  pre/post — same launchctl calls, same stop_direct invocation.

Verification:

  - `nix build` exit 0; all patches apply cleanly.
  - `bash -n manage.sh` returns 0 (syntax valid).
  - On NixOS post-install:
      cat ~/.config/systemd/user/pai-pulse.service
        → expected unit content; ExecStart contains absolute
          ~/.bun/bin/bun OR /nix/store/.../bin/bun depending on
          environment; Environment line contains PATH with the
          Nix store paths from the wrapper.
      systemctl --user is-active pai-pulse.service → active
      kill -9 $(pgrep -f bun.*pulse.ts); sleep 35
        → systemctl --user is-active → active (Restart=always
          fired after RestartSec=30).
      logout / login: pgrep -f bun.*pulse.ts → returns PID
        (auto-start on login fired).
      bash manage.sh stop → systemctl --user is-active → inactive
        (clean stop, no respawn).
      bash manage.sh uninstall → unit file removed, daemon-reload
        run, daemon stopped.
  - macOS regression check (manual via patched file inspection):
    `start)` and `install)` macOS branches structurally unchanged;
    `stop)` and `uninstall)` macOS branches gain stop_direct call
    inside the `if $IS_MACOS` block (matched move from below the
    if-fi). No semantic change to macOS execution.

Files / hunks:

  PAI/PULSE/manage.sh
    @@ -9,6 +9,8 @@        + SERVICE_NAME, SERVICE_DST
    @@ -16,6 +18,19 @@      + IS_SYSTEMD detection
    @@ -58,6 +73,40 @@      + write_unit() helper
    @@ -67,6 +116,8 @@      + start) elif systemd branch
    @@ -76,8 +127,12 @@     ~ stop) regroup + elif systemd branch
    @@ -87,7 +142,15 @@     ~ status) prepend systemd reporting
    @@ -123,6 +186,8 @@     + install) cleanup elif systemd
    @@ -132,6 +197,13 @@     + install) start elif systemd
    @@ -157,8 +229,14 @@     ~ uninstall) regroup + elif systemd

---
--- a/Releases/v5.0.0/.claude/PAI/PULSE/manage.sh
+++ b/Releases/v5.0.0/.claude/PAI/PULSE/manage.sh
@@ -9,6 +9,8 @@
 PID_FILE="$PULSE_DIR/state/pulse.pid"
 STATE_FILE="$PULSE_DIR/state/state.json"
 LOG_DIR="$PULSE_DIR/logs"
+SERVICE_NAME="pai-pulse"
+SERVICE_DST="$HOME/.config/systemd/user/${SERVICE_NAME}.service"

 # Detect platform: macOS uses launchctl, Linux uses direct process management.
 IS_MACOS=false
@@ -16,6 +18,19 @@
   IS_MACOS=true
 fi

+# Detect systemd-user availability for Linux daemon management. Linux distros
+# without systemd (Alpine, some containers, NixOS without systemd-as-PID-1) fall
+# back to start_direct's nohup approach. The check requires both the systemctl
+# binary and the runtime-dir socket — bare systemctl presence isn't sufficient
+# (systemctl ships in PATH inside chroots and minimal images, but the per-user
+# manager isn't actually running there).
+IS_SYSTEMD=false
+if ! $IS_MACOS \
+   && [ -d "${XDG_RUNTIME_DIR:-/run/user/$(id -u)}/systemd" ] \
+   && command -v systemctl >/dev/null 2>&1; then
+  IS_SYSTEMD=true
+fi
+
 # Resolve bun's actual location for the launchd job. The public plist
 # template ships with `__BUN_PATH__` so the job works for both brew users
 # (/opt/homebrew/bin/bun) and curl-installer users (~/.bun/bin/bun).
@@ -58,6 +73,40 @@
   fi
 }

+# ─── Helper: write systemd user unit (Linux + systemd) ────
+# Bake the install-time PATH into the unit so claude/bun/jq/curl/git resolve
+# regardless of how the user's systemd-user inherits its environment. Whoever
+# ran `manage.sh install` (the pai installer wrapper, the user's shell, or a
+# packaging tool) has already exported a functional PATH; capturing it here
+# gives the daemon the same toolchain its install context had. Re-running
+# `manage.sh install` after a PATH change re-bakes the unit. RestartSec=30
+# matches launchd's ThrottleInterval=30 in com.pai.pulse.plist for cross-
+# platform parity.
+write_unit() {
+  mkdir -p "$(dirname "$SERVICE_DST")"
+  cat > "$SERVICE_DST" <<EOF
+[Unit]
+Description=PAI Pulse — local runtime for PAI services
+After=network.target
+ConditionPathExists=$PULSE_DIR/pulse.ts
+
+[Service]
+Type=simple
+WorkingDirectory=$PULSE_DIR
+ExecStart=$BUN_PATH run pulse.ts
+Restart=always
+RestartSec=30
+StandardOutput=append:$LOG_DIR/pulse-stdout.log
+StandardError=append:$LOG_DIR/pulse-stderr.log
+Environment=HOME=$HOME
+Environment="PATH=$PATH"
+
+[Install]
+WantedBy=default.target
+EOF
+  systemctl --user daemon-reload
+}
+
 case "$1" in
   start)
     if $IS_MACOS; then
@@ -67,6 +116,8 @@
         sed -e "s|__HOME__|$HOME|g" -e "s|__BUN_PATH__|$BUN_PATH|g" "$PLIST_SRC" > "$PLIST_DST"
       fi
       launchctl load "$PLIST_DST" 2>/dev/null
+    elif $IS_SYSTEMD && [ -f "$SERVICE_DST" ]; then
+      systemctl --user start "$SERVICE_NAME.service"
     else
       start_direct
     fi
@@ -76,8 +127,12 @@
   stop)
     if $IS_MACOS; then
       launchctl unload "$PLIST_DST" 2>/dev/null
+      stop_direct
+    elif $IS_SYSTEMD && [ -f "$SERVICE_DST" ]; then
+      systemctl --user stop "$SERVICE_NAME.service" 2>/dev/null || true
+    else
+      stop_direct
     fi
-    stop_direct
     ;;

   restart)
@@ -87,7 +142,15 @@
     ;;

   status)
-    if [ -f "$PID_FILE" ]; then
+    if $IS_SYSTEMD && [ -f "$SERVICE_DST" ]; then
+      if systemctl --user is-active --quiet "$SERVICE_NAME.service"; then
+        PID=$(systemctl --user show -p MainPID --value "$SERVICE_NAME.service")
+        UPTIME=$(ps -p "$PID" -o etime= 2>/dev/null | xargs)
+        echo "PAI Pulse: RUNNING (systemd, PID $PID, uptime $UPTIME)"
+      else
+        echo "PAI Pulse: NOT RUNNING (systemd inactive)"
+      fi
+    elif [ -f "$PID_FILE" ]; then
       PID=$(cat "$PID_FILE")
       if ps -p "$PID" > /dev/null 2>&1; then
         UPTIME=$(ps -p "$PID" -o etime= | xargs)
@@ -123,6 +186,8 @@
       if [ -f "$PLIST_DST" ]; then
         launchctl unload "$PLIST_DST" 2>/dev/null || true
       fi
+    elif $IS_SYSTEMD && [ -f "$SERVICE_DST" ]; then
+      systemctl --user stop "$SERVICE_NAME.service" 2>/dev/null || true
     fi
     pkill -9 -f "bun.*pulse.ts" 2>/dev/null || true
     sleep 1
@@ -132,6 +197,13 @@
       # no-op on plists that already have literal paths.
       sed -e "s|__HOME__|$HOME|g" -e "s|__BUN_PATH__|$BUN_PATH|g" "$PLIST_SRC" > "$PLIST_DST"
       launchctl load "$PLIST_DST"
+    elif $IS_SYSTEMD; then
+      # Linux + systemd: parity with launchd (auto-start on login, restart on
+      # crash, persists across reboots). Without this, Pulse on Linux runs
+      # only until first crash or graceful shutdown — see start_direct() above
+      # for the non-systemd fallback.
+      write_unit
+      systemctl --user enable --now "$SERVICE_NAME.service"
     else
       start_direct
     fi
@@ -157,8 +229,14 @@
     if $IS_MACOS; then
       launchctl unload "$PLIST_DST" 2>/dev/null
       rm -f "$PLIST_DST"
+      stop_direct
+    elif $IS_SYSTEMD && [ -f "$SERVICE_DST" ]; then
+      systemctl --user disable --now "$SERVICE_NAME.service" 2>/dev/null || true
+      rm -f "$SERVICE_DST"
+      systemctl --user daemon-reload
+    else
+      stop_direct
     fi
-    stop_direct
     echo "PAI Pulse uninstalled"
     ;;
